  "text": "2 For instance, callers who are in need of help are more likely to switch between expressions of fear and expressions of sadness, rather than expressions of anger-fear and anger-sadness, since the former two are examples of supplication emotions. Switching between anger-fear and anger-sadness is thus less expected as it implies a relation between a confrontation and supplication emotion. The measurements followed a Likert-convention, frequently used in previous studies of emotion perception, and contained a scale for each emotion of the three emotions, where 0 equaled no expression and 10 very clear emotional expression (cf. [CITATION_1] .",
